SIMPLE: gospel
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gospel
<hw>Gos"pel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>gospel</ets>, <ets>godspel</ets>, AS. <ets>godspell</ets>;
<ets>god</ets> God + <ets>spell</ets> story, tale. See <er>God</er>, and
<er>Spell</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Glad tidings; especially, the good news concerning
Christ, the Kingdom of God, and salvation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Jesus went about all Galilee, teaching in their synagogues,
and preaching the <qex>gospel</qex> of the kingdom.</q> <rj><qau>Matt.
iv. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The steadfast belief of the promises of the <qex>gospel</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ It is probable that <xex>gospel</xex> is from. OE.
<xex>godspel</xex>, God story, the narrative concerning God; but it was
early confused with <xex>god spell</xex>, good story, good tidings, and
was so used by the translators of the Authorized version of Scripture.
This use has been retained in most cases in the Revised
Version.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus the literal sense [of <qex>gospel</qex>] is the
⟦ldquo⟧narrative of God,⟦rdquo⟧ <it>i. e.</it>, the life of Christ.</q>
<rj><qau>Skeat.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the four narratives of the life and death of
Jesus Christ, written by Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A selection from one of the gospels, for use in a
religious service; <as>as, the <ex>gospel</ex> for the
day</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Any system of religious doctrine; sometimes, any
system of political doctrine or social philosophy; <as>as, this
political <ex>gospel</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Anything propounded or accepted as infallibly true;
<as>as, they took his words for <ex>gospel</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If any one thinks this expression hyperbolical, I shall only ask
him to read <xex>⟦OE⟧dipus</xex>, instead of taking the traditional
witticisms about Lee for <qex>gospel</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Saintsbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gospel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gospel
<hw>Gos"pel</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Accordant with, or relating to, the
gospel; evangelical; <as>as, <ex>gospel</ex> righteousness</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Bp. Warburton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gospel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gospel
<hw>Gos"pel</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To instruct in the gospel.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gospeler</ent>⟦br⟧
